Title: Prey
Author: Michael Crichton
My Review:
New Vocabulary

Monastic: relating to monks, nuns or others or the buildings in which they live. "the room was monastic..." - simple/conventional, like a monk's room

Bluntness: a quality meaning uncompromisingly forthright or straightforward. "An engineer's bluntness."

Perforations: a hole made by boring or piercing. "the glass had little perforations." - small holes

Ubiquitous: present, appearing, or found everywhere. "his ubiquitous Walkman..." - Walkmans are very common a lot of people own them

Endowed: to provide with a quality, ability, or asset. "had to be endowed with rudimentary intelligence." - given an intelligence

Sinuous: having many curves or turns. "In a kind of sinuous movement."

Intermittently: at irregular intervals; not continuously or steadily. "And, intermittently, the cloud began to thin out." - it thinned at irregular time intervals

Superimposed: placed/ laid over something else, typically so that both things are still evident. "a series of superimposed rhythms." - the swarm is moving in rhythms that fit over each other.

Undulate: move or go in a smooth up and down motion. "Watching the cloud swirl and undulate as it came closer."

Obsequious: obedient or attentive to an excessive degree. "Ricky was obsequious to management..." - overly eager to please everyone

Modality: a particular mode in which something exists or is experienced or expressed. "Their main sensory modality is vision." - the mode in which they experience the world is vision

Vigilance: the action/state of keeping careful watch for possible danger or difficulties. "Large numbers of animals increased vigilance."

Stymie: prevent or hinder the progress of. "these predators were stymied."

Pantomime: an entertainment in which performers express meaning through gestures. "They were pantomiming something else."

Confluence: the act of process of merging. "a confluence of chance events" - A merging

Laconic: using very few words. "won't work Jack, Ricky said laconically."

Title: The Martian
Author: Andy Weir
My Review:
Germinate: (of a seed or spore) begin to put out shoots after a period of dormancy. "the Martian soil will be ready for plants to germinate in."

Endeavor: an attempt to achieve a goal. "I plan to dedicate all of it to achieve this endeavor."

Prolific: (of a plant animal or person) producing much fruit or foliage or offspring. "They grow prolifically." - producing a high yield

Tripe: nonsense; rubbish. "... from Commander Lewis's inexhaustible collection of seventies tripe."

Auspicious: conductive to success; favorable. "... to stay out of everyone's way while recording the auspicious moment."

Parse: analyze (a string of text) into logical syntactic components, typically in order to test conformability to a logical grammar. "... there's a spot in the code where it's got the parsed bytes."

Roust: cause to get up or start moving; rouse. "Having rousted the troops..."

Proffer: hold out something to someone for acceptance; offer. "... Vogel replied, taking the proffered breakfast."

Cacophony: a harsh discordant mixture of sounds. "The cacophony grew louder by the minute."

Doff: remove (an item of clothing). "Once it pressurized, he quickly doffed his suit."

Insubordination: defiance of authority; refusal to obey orders. "Insubordination will not help."

Gantry: a bridge-like overhead structure with a platform supporting equipment such as a crane. "The retaining clamps ejected from the gantry, falling to the ground."

Oppressive: overwhelming or depressing to the spirit or senses "... an oppressive calm replaced the previous cacophony."

Schlep: haul or carry (something heavy or awkward). " ... I have to schlep to the rover five times a day."

Surmountable: able to be overcome. "The hole where Airlock 1 used to be is huge, but surmountable."

Forlornly: desolate or dreary, unhappy or miserable, as in a feeling, condition or appearance. "He looked forlornly at the blue folder..."

Jaded: tired, bored, or lacking enthusiasm, typically after having had too much of something. "... after a lifetime of commanding sailors, she's got an unfairly jaded view."

Heralded: be a sign that something is about to happen. "The worst moments in my life are heralded by small observations." - indicated

Lecherous: having or showing excessive or offensive sexual desire. "You lecherous home wrecker"

Intrepid: fearless; adventurous (often used for a humorous effect). "There wasn't much left for our intrepid hero."

Coruscate: (of light) flash or sparkle. "A mild cheer coruscated through crowds worldwide." -flash

Conflagration: a large disastrous fire. "... became an uncontrolled conflagration."

Title: Ender’s Game (Ender's Saga, #1)
Author: Orson Scott Card
My Review:
Rescind (v): to take away; remove. "He was sure they would like to rescind the wavers..."

Supine (adj): lying on the back or with the face upward; prone (slightly different) "Ender walked to Stilson's supine body and..."

Mirth (n): gladness or gaiety as shown by or accompanied by laughter; cheer. "Loud, but with real mirth..."

Commiserate (v): to feel or express sympathy; condole. "Mother came home and commiserated with Ender about the monitor."

Extenuate (v): tending to lessen the real or apparent seriousness of something by making partial excuse; mitigate. "We're considering the extenuating circumstances."

Circumvent (v): to manage to get around especially by ingenuity or stratagem; bypass. "because they were able to circumvent the law and have a Third."

Unstintingly (adj): not restraining or holding back : giving or being given freely or generously; bighearted. "Completely, unstintingly, she's devoted to you."

Requisition (n): the act of formally requiring or calling on someone to perform an action; demand. "So we requisitioned you."

Scrupulous (adj): punctiliously exact; painstaking. "The boy sitting next to Ender was scrupulously careful not to touch him."

Extricate (v): to free or remove from an entanglement or difficulty; disengage. "every time, though, he extricated himself and went back."

Raucous (adj): disagreeably harsh or strident; hoarse. "Their laughter was raucous."

Contempt (n): the act of despising: the state of mind of the one who despises; disdain. "... trying to disassociate himself from her contempt."

Magnanimous (adj): showing and suggesting a lofty and courageous spirit; lordly. "... and rubbed his nose in it by being magnanimous."

Stolid (adj): having or expressing little or no sensibility; unemotional. ". Bass Andre Valenti was stolid as Tamara’s father.

Requisition (v): the act of formally requiring or calling upon someone to perform an act; demand. "... but was requisitioning it from the landslide computer."

Puerile (adj): juvenile. "He acted as though he was excited about the puerile lesson of the day."

Syndicate (v): to subject to or manage as a syndicate - a business concern that sells materials for publication in a number of newspapers or periodicals simultaneously. "... when Valentine's column got syndicated into other newspapers."

Sequester (v): to set apart; segregate. "If we can't solve it this way, we'll sequester your family and solve it that way."

Acquiescence (n): passive acceptance or submission; compliance. "his acquiescence calmed her."

Adroit (adj) : having or showing skill, cleverness, or resourcefulness in handling situations; artful. "... and he caught himself adroitly." - showing skill

Insolent (adj): insulting contemptuous in speech or conduct; overbearing. "It was Bean, already in his flash suit, looking insolent."

Contemptuous (adj): manifesting, feeling, or expressing deep hatred of disapproval : feeling or showing contempt. "Of course, Ender said contemptuously."

Ineptitude (n) : the quality or state of being inept; incompetence. "It was only Bonzo's ineptitude that had saved them."

Disingenuous (adj): lacking in candor or sincereness typically by pretending that one knows less about something than one really does. "Do not be disingenuous with me."

Percolate (v): to ooze or trickle through a permeable substance; seep "The name Ender Wiggin has percolated through high command."

Unconscionable (adj): shockingly unfair or unjust; unreasonable. "You have no military men to break the disturbance. It is unconscionable."

Corroborate (v): to support with evidence or authority: make more certain. "As if to corroborate Bean's statement..."

Toady (n) : one who flatters in hope of gaining favors; sycophant. "To show the politicians who toadied to the Russians."

Subservient (adj): useful in an inferior capacity "the peace would end up subservient to them in everything."

Monopoly (n): eculsive ownership through legal privelage, command of supply, or concentrated action. "Peter didn't have a monopoly on that."

Fastidious (adj): showing or demanding excessive delicacy or care. "There were still waterbirds taking their little fastidious steps into the salt water."

Apathy (n): lack of feeling or emotion; impassiveness. "He looked at Ender with an expression that only bespoke apathy."

Attrition (n): the act of weakening or exhausting by constant harassment, abuse, or attack.
"They were able to wear him down by attrition."

Petulant (adj): insolent or rude in speech or behavior. "You can be as petulant as you want tomorrow."

Acquit (v): to discharge completely (as from accusation or obligation). "Not really I new I'd be acquitted."

Accrue (v): to come into existence as a legally enforceable claim. "I still have a few years of leave accrued."

Title: The Drawing of the Three (The Dark Tower, #2)
Author: Stephen King
My Review: The Gunslinger, Roland, is separated from some of his fingers and toes on the beach of his world.  He is weak and begins to head north based on some instinct.  He encounters the first door that allows him to enter the mind of Eddie Dean, a drug addict.  Roland, helps Eddie to smuggle drugs through customs by bringing them into his own world.  Roland follows Eddie inside of his head and helps him to deliver the drugs to Balazar. Balazar doesn't like it and a gunfight begins in which Eddie and Roland are victorious. All of Balazar's men are killed.  Eddie returns to the Gunslinger's home and they begin the trek to the next door.  Eddie must, resentfully, carry the Gunslinger as he is too sick to walk.  The second door leads to the mind of a schizophrenic named Detta Walker/Odetta Walker.  The women has a modest and dangerous personality as a result of a brick being dropped on her head as a child.  She is also legless because she was pushed in front of a train ijn her twenties.  Roland enters her mind and frees her from the cops as she is caught stealing jewelry.
